{"award_age":71.0,"bio_image":"full\/e0329aa0406f749498a3002bc7710d122662d108.jpg","category":"Physics","country":"United States","date_of_birth":"1931-10-06T00:00:00.000Z","date_of_death":null,"gender":"male","image_urls":["http:\/\/upload.wikimedia.org\/wikipedia\/commons\/thumb\/0\/03\/RiccardoGiacconi.jpg\/180px-RiccardoGiacconi.jpg"],"link":"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Riccardo_Giacconi","mini_bio":"<p><b>Riccardo Giacconi<\/b> (born October 6, 1931) is an American <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Nobel_Prize\" title=\"Nobel Prize\">Nobel Prize<\/a>-winning <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Astrophysicist\" title=\"Astrophysicist\" class=\"mw-redirect\">astrophysicist<\/a> who laid the foundations of <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/X-ray_astronomy\" title=\"X-ray astronomy\">X-ray astronomy<\/a>. He is currently a professor at the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Johns_Hopkins_University\" title=\"Johns Hopkins University\">Johns Hopkins University<\/a>.<\/p><p>Born in <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Genoa\" title=\"Genoa\">Genoa<\/a>, Italy, Giacconi received his <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Laurea#Former_status_of_the_Laurea_degree\" title=\"Laurea\">Laurea<\/a> from the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/University_of_Milan\" title=\"University of Milan\">University of Milan<\/a> before moving to the US to pursue a career in <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Astrophysics\" title=\"Astrophysics\">astrophysics<\/a> research.<\/p><p>Since cosmic X-ray radiation is absorbed by the Earth's atmosphere, space-based telescopes are needed for X-ray astronomy. Applying himself to this problem, Giacconi worked on the instrumentation for X-ray astronomy; from rocket-borne detectors in the late 1950s and early 1960s, to <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Uhuru_(satellite)\" title=\"Uhuru (satellite)\">Uhuru<\/a>, the first orbiting X-ray astronomy satellite, in the 1970s. Giacconi's pioneering research continued in 1978 with the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Einstein_Observatory\" title=\"Einstein Observatory\">Einstein Observatory<\/a>, the first fully imaging X-ray telescope put into space, and later with the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Chandra_X-ray_Observatory\" title=\"Chandra X-ray Observatory\">Chandra X-ray Observatory<\/a>, which was launched in 1999 and is still in operation. Giacconi also applied his expertise to other fields of astronomy, becoming the first director of the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Space_Telescope_Science_Institute\" title=\"Space Telescope Science Institute\">Space Telescope Science Institute<\/a>, the science operations center for the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Hubble_Space_Telescope\" title=\"Hubble Space Telescope\">Hubble Space Telescope<\/a>.<\/p><p>Giacconi was awarded a share of the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Nobel_Prize_in_Physics\" title=\"Nobel Prize in Physics\">Nobel Prize in Physics<\/a> in 2002 \"for pioneering contributions to astrophysics, which have led to the discovery of cosmic X-ray sources\".<sup id=\"cite_ref-NobelCitation_1-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Riccardo_Giacconi#cite_note-NobelCitation-1\"><span>[<\/span>1<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup> The other shares of the Prize in that year were awarded to <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Masatoshi_Koshiba\" title=\"Masatoshi Koshiba\">Masatoshi Koshiba<\/a> and <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Raymond_Davis,_Jr.\" title=\"Raymond Davis, Jr.\">Raymond Davis, Jr.<\/a>.<\/p><p>Giacconi has held the positions of professor of physics and astronomy (1982\u20131997) and research professor (since 1998) at <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Johns_Hopkins_University\" title=\"Johns Hopkins University\">Johns Hopkins University<\/a>, and is now University Professor. During that time he also held the position of Director General of the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/European_Southern_Observatory\" title=\"European Southern Observatory\">European Southern Observatory<\/a> (ESO) (1993\u20131999). He is currently <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Principal_investigator\" title=\"Principal investigator\">principal investigator<\/a> for the Chandra Deep Field-South project with <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/NASA\" title=\"NASA\">NASA<\/a>'s <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Chandra_X-ray_Observatory\" title=\"Chandra X-ray Observatory\">Chandra X-ray Observatory<\/a>.<\/p>","name":"Riccardo Giacconi","place_of_birth":"Genoa ,  Italy","place_of_death":null,"text":"Riccardo Giacconi ,  born in Italy , Physics, 2002","year":2002.0}